<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910305-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>910305-0036.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Flying Sardines</HL><DATE>03/05/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17</SO><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><LP>   In your Feb. 11 article discussing the steps that airlinepassengers may take beforehand to increase their chances ofsurviving a crash (&quot;With Foresight, Fliers Can Cut Risks ofTravel&quot;), Aviation Safety Institute President John Galipaultnotes that air-crash studies reveal &quot;seats are too closetogether, the aisles aren't wide enough. That's always atradeoff for the airlines. They want to pack them in.&quot;Stuffing more passengers into the cabin can hardly be calleda tradeoff. While airlines benefit from the increasedrevenue, it's the traveler who pays the price throughdiminished safety.   Michael G. McGinty</LP><TEXT>   Plainville, Conn.</TEXT></DOC>